00:56:13,730 --> 00:56:17,730
Go on, Mike. Get in close, Mike, now start slowing.

443
00:56:17,730 --> 00:56:19,030
OK.

444
00:56:19,130 --> 00:56:23,430
It's still not right and now time is running out.

445
00:56:23,530 --> 00:56:25,330
I think the light's going.

446
00:56:25,730 --> 00:56:27,530
Shall we do one last take?

447
00:56:27,630 --> 00:56:31,830
All right. Because these ones here, we're losing the light on them.

448
00:56:31,920 --> 00:56:34,820
Try and get a shot that's going past here if it's smooth.

449
00:56:36,820 --> 00:56:41,720
One, two, three, and we're away.

450
00:56:42,120 --> 00:56:43,020
Take 17.

451
00:56:48,720 --> 00:56:51,120
And it's looking good.

452
00:56:51,120 --> 00:56:56,620
OK, start slowing, Mike. OK, keep it going, keep it going.

453
00:56:59,520 --> 00:57:01,520
Success at last.

454
00:57:05,610 --> 00:57:10,210
With the technique now working, the crew rig more and more shots

455
00:57:10,310 --> 00:57:15,210
to give an aerial perspective on the monarch phenomenon.

456
00:57:21,110 --> 00:57:26,010
His work advising the crew over, Lincoln continues the observations

457
00:57:26,110 --> 00:57:28,910
he's been making for over a quarter of a century.

458
00:57:28,910 --> 00:57:32,110
Although the butterflies are still here in immense numbers,

459
00:57:32,110 --> 00:57:36,010
he's worried there is a threat to their survival.

460
00:57:36,000 --> 00:57:42,500
The big, huge influx, maybe sometimes as many as two billion butterflies,

461
00:57:42,500 --> 00:57:46,700
flying down into this tiny area of 30 by 60 miles,

462
00:57:46,700 --> 00:57:51,200
is thoroughly endangered by illegal logging.

463
00:57:51,200 --> 00:57:55,100
If the forest is not protected the phenomenon will be lost.

464
00:58:07,100 --> 00:58:08,400
It'd be a disaster.

465
00:58:08,690 --> 00:58:15,290
I mean, it would be like taking the Mona Lisa out of the Parisian museum and,

466
00:58:15,690 --> 00:58:16,890
and burning it up.

